Group Proposal¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains the records of about 300 patients who suffer from heart diseases. Using the techniques learnt in DSCI 100, we will try to determine a relationship between the presence of heart diseases and other factors such as age, cholestrol, and heartrate. We will visualize our data through stacked bar graphs and histograms to see if such a relationship can be established. To begin with our analysis, we make sure our data is tidy. To do this, we incorporate principles of data wrangling to obtain a clean dataset. As you will see below, we split our data into train and test. Train dataset is used to fit our model, which we will then test on the Test model. Using various visualization techniques we will see if our attempt at predicting the onset of heart disease based on different factors of age and cholestrol is successful or not.

This dataset was imported from processed.cleveland.data

Preliminary exploratory data analysis:¶

reading the data frame¶

  • since it is the csv file. We use read_csv() function to read the file. Then we noticed that there's no column names in the data set. We fill the names through the disease name file. Finally,we make column into the correct data type.

library(tidyverse)
library(readr)

df<-read_table("https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.cleveland.data",col_names = FALSE)
df1<-separate(df,X1,sep = ",",into =c("age","sex","cp","trestbps","chol","fbs","restecg","thalach","exang","oldpeak","slope","ca",'thal','num'))


df1$age<-as.numeric(df1$age)
df1$sex<-as.factor(df1$sex)
df1$cp<-as.factor(df1$cp)
df1$trestbps<-as.numeric(df1$trestbps)
df1$chol<-as.numeric(df1$chol)
df1$fbs<-as.factor(df1$fbs)

df1$num<-as.factor(df1$num)

  • Putting all the variables in to the model will cause over fitting which means the model cannot work properly towards the data which is not being included in the training data set.

  • Thus we need to do the variable selection for our model. In here, we made a variable importance plot from random forest. It can helps us to verify which variable is important to help us to do the classification.

  • We can visualize the distribution by using histograms and barplots to easily identify the differences between diagnosis of heart disease.
  • We can visualize the results by plotting Predicted vs Observed in a table.
  • We can further visualize the results by using a boxplot to compare these models.

Expected outcomes and significance:¶

  • We expect that people with higher age,greater heart rate,and ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest tends to suffer from heart diseases. This makes sense since our heart weakens due to old age and high heart rate achieved means that the heart rate is not steady or isn't working efficiently. Too low and too high ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest means that the heart's ability to function is diminishing. We also expect people with more than 0 major vessels colored by fluoroscopy and having asymptomatic chest pain tends to suffer from heart diseases, since people with more than 0 major vessels colored by fluoroscopy have problems in major vessels and major vessels are strongly connected with the heart. Also, the asymptomatic chest pain means that people cannot detect where the source of pain comes from. This could indicate a problem with their heart.

  • Looking at the bar charts and histograms above, we were right in choosing our factors to predict the onset of heart diseases. We see that people suffering from heart diseases are older, have higher cholestrol and a more extreme heart rate.

  • This analysis has a large impact on our lives. This could help doctors predict the onset of heart diseases, and help educate people and encourage them to take better care of their health. This shows that people who exercise regularly and maintain their cholestrol are statistically less likely to suffer from an ailment of the heart.

  • This analysis leads to the question that can we make a better model, with more factors and variables that can help us better predict the onset of heart diseases.
